Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @butternut squash{1}. Halve lengthways, scoop out the seeds (no need to peel). Chop widthways into 2cm wide semicircles. Pop onto a #baking tray{}. Halve the @premium tomato mix{125%g} then pick the @sage{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Add to the tray with the squash. Drizzle everything with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat in the oil and seasoning.

Pop the baking tray on the middle shelf of the oven to roast until tender and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> The tomatoes will collapse and caramelise - this is exactly what we want!

Pour the @water{200%ml} for the beans into a large #saucepan{} on high heat. Add the @butter beans{1} and @vegetable stock powder{1/2}. Stir to dissolve the stock powder, bring to the boil then reduce the heat to medium. Simmer until the water has almost disappeared, ~{10-15%minutes}, then use a #potato masher{} to the mash the beans into a smooth paste. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, put a large #frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil). Pop the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g}, @thyme{1/2}, @lemon{1/2}(zested), and @hazelnuts{25%g} into the pan with a pinch of salt and pepper. Toast until lightly golden, stirring often, ~{4-6%minutes}. Once coloured, transfer to a small #bowl{} (keep the pan!).

Wipe out the frying pan with some #kitchen paper{}(some), return to medium heat and add the @chopped cavolo nero{100%g} along with the @garlic clove{1}(minced), a pinch of salt and pepper and a splash of @water{} for the cavolo nero, then cover the pan with a lid or some #tin foil{}. Cook on a medium-high heat until tender and wilted, ~{3-5%minutes}. When done, stir in the @reduced fat creme fraiche{75%g} and a squeeze of lemon juice to taste.

When you are ready to serve, divide the butter bean mash and creamy cavolo nero between your plates. Place the roasted veggies on top then sprinkle over the lemon and thyme breadcrumbs. Dig in!